    (22,'progress_bench_comp','<p>Student Growth measures the percent of students in a school that made “typical one-year growth” across reading and math tests, in 2nd through 8th grades.</p>\r\n<p>Nearly every school in Detroit uses either NWEA’s MAP test or Scantron Performance Series test. Both tests are computer-adaptive meaning they are taken using a computer  and the test’s rigor adjusts based on the student’s abilities.  Both tests are also considered growth-to-achievement standard tests, meaning they measure where a student begins the school year academically, sets a one academic year achievement target based on that first test, then measures how close that student got to the target during the last test.  The target is called “typical growth” because it is based on how much growth is “typical” or reasonable based on results from similar students across the country. Students either meet their one-year growth target or do not meet their target.</p>\r\n<p>With permission from K-8 schools, Excellent Schools Detroit received aggregated school-level data directly from NWEA and Scantron for the percentage of students meeting their annual growth targets using the fall and spring assessment windows, as set by the companies using large nationwide cohorts. Both assessments set subject-specific growth targets for students based on what is “normal” for students with similar baseline (fall) test scores.&nbsp; The measure Excellent Schools Detroit used is simply the percentage of students who met or exceeded their growth targets.</p>\r\n  <TABLE>\r\n   <TBODY>\r\n     <TR>\r\n        <TD>\r\n          NWEA/Scantron Composite\r\n       </TD>\r\n     </TR>\r\n   </TBODY>\r\n    <TBODY>\r\n     <TR>\r\n        <TD>\r\n          <BR>\r\n          \r\n        </TD>\r\n       <TD>\r\n          Floor\r\n       </TD>\r\n       <TD>\r\n          17%\r\n       </TD>\r\n     </TR>\r\n   </TBODY>\r\n    <TBODY>\r\n     <TR>\r\n        <TD>\r\n          <BR>\r\n          \r\n        </