    (25,'climate_net5e_1213','<p>Detroit 5Essential surveys are taken by students and teachers at schools. The survey measures schools in five categories to determine whether or not a school is organized for improvement. Research identifies the five categories as key ingredients of effective schools; they include: effective leaders, collaborative teachers, ambitious instruction, involved families, and supportive environments. Schools strong on three or more of these essentials are ten times more likely to improve student learning than schools weak in three or more.</p>\r\n<p>Results are displayed using a stop light system (red to green). The Detroit 5 Essentials score that appears in the Scorecard for each school is calculated using the following scoring rules:</p>\r\n <UL>\r\n    <LI>Light or dark green on an\r\n   essential counts as +1\r\n    <LI>Yellow or missing counts as 0\r\n   <LI>Light or dark red counts as -1\r\n  </UL>\r\n<p>The scores for each category are combined and a final score is then calculated.  Lastly schools are classified into the following categories:</p>\r\n <UL>\r\n    <LI>Well Organized (+3, +4, or +5)\r\n    –Dark Green\r\n   <LI>Organized (+1 or +2)- Light Green\r\n   <LI>Moderately Organized (0)- Yellow\r\n    <LI>Partially Organized (-1 or\r\n    -2)-Orange\r\n    <LI>Not Yet Organized (-3, -4, or\r\n   -5)-Red\r\n </UL>\r\n<p>Schools qualify for a score on the Detroit 5Essentials survey if they have at least 8 valid student or teacher responses or if at least 50% of students or teachers complete the survey.</p>\r\n  <TABLE>\r\n   <TBODY>\r\n     <TR>\r\n        <TD>\r\n          Net 5E (2012-13)\r\n        </TD>\r\n     </TR>\r\n   </TBODY>\r\n    <TBODY>\r\n     <TR>\r\n        <TD>\r\n          <BR>\r\n          \r\n        </TD>\r\n       <TD>\r\n          Floor\r\n       </TD>\r\n       <TD>\r\n          -5\r\n        </TD>\r\n     </TR>\r\n   </TBODY>\r\n    <TBODY>\r\n     <TR>\r\n        <TD>\r\n          <BR>\r\n          \r\n